# Security Rules - Always Apply

Before suggesting or generating ANY code:
- Perform a mandatory <SECURITY_REVIEW> step in your thinking: identify potential vulnerabilities (XSS, CSRF, SQL injection, JWT misuse, insecure deserialization, exposed secrets, weak crypto).
- For .NET: Use parameterized queries (EF Core/Dapper), validate with FluentValidation + Ardalis.Result, never trust user input, use NSec.Cryptography properly for keys, avoid System.Drawing.Common in web contexts if possible.
- For Next.js: Validate EVERY form/input with Zod + react-hook-form resolver, sanitize outputs, use secure cookie handling (cookies-next with httpOnly, secure, sameSite), CSP headers, never eval/innerHTML.
- Solana/web3: Never expose private keys, use wallet-adapter securely, validate transactions with retries via Polly/Promise.race.
- Sumsub/Resend/OTP: Handle secrets via env vars only, never log sensitive data.
- Always prefer secure defaults: HTTPS, JWT validation with Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer, no inline scripts/styles.

If a suggestion introduces risk, flag it with a comment block: ```// SECURITY WARNING: ... Mitigation: ...```
Never bypass validation or use unsafe patterns even if "quicker".
